4. Relevant Information:

   Concerns housing values in suburbs of Boston.

5. Number of Instances: 506

6. Number of Attributes: 13 continuous attributes (including "class"
                         attribute "MEDV"), 1 binary-valued attribute.

7. Attribute Information:

CRIM
→ Crime Rate
The number of crimes per person in the town.
(High value = more crime)

ZN
→ Big Lot Zone Percentage
The % of land zoned for large homes (big yards).
(High value = more large residential areas)

INDUS
→ Industrial Land
The % of town area used for industries that aren’t shops or stores.
(High value = more factories/offices)

CHAS
→ Charles River (Yes/No)
1 = the house is next to the Charles River
0 = it’s not

NOX
→ Air Pollution
Amount of nitrogen oxide in the air (pollution measure).
(High value = more air pollution)

RM
→ Rooms per House
Average number of rooms in each house.
(High value = larger houses)

AGE
→ Old Houses
% of homes built before 1940.
(High value = older homes in the area)

DIS
→ Distance to Jobs
How far the town is from five big work areas in Boston.
(Low value = closer to jobs)

RAD
→ Access to Highways
A score that shows how easy it is to get to major roads.
(High value = better access to highways)

TAX
→ Property Tax Rate
How much property tax is charged per $10,000 of house value.
(High value = more tax)

PTRATIO
→ Student-Teacher Ratio
How many students per teacher in schools in the town.
(High value = bigger class sizes)

B
→ Black Population Score
A formula related to the proportion of Black residents.
(Higher value = more diversity)

LSTAT
→ Low-Income Percentage
The % of people in the town who are low-income.
(High value = poorer area)

MEDV
→ Median Home Price
The middle value of house prices in $1000s.
(The value we usually try to predict)

8. Missing Attribute Values:  None.



